07335nam a22012135i 9783110346831DE-B159720211217065530.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||211217t20142014gw     fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)890071088  a97831103468317 a10.1515/97831103468312doi  a(DE-B1597)246502  a(OCoLC)889303803  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP40.5.L54bM489 2014 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a306.4422300aMediatization and Sociolinguistic Change /ced. by Jannis Androutsopoulos. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2014] 4c©2014  a1 online resource (557 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 alinguae & litterae : Publications of the School of Language and Literature Freiburg Institute for Advanced Studies ,x1869-7054 ;v360 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis is the first volume to focus on the role of media in processes of linguistic change, one of the most contested issues in contemporary sociolinguistics. Its 17 chapters and five section commentaries present cutting-edge research from variationist and interactional sociolinguistics, media linguistics, language ideology research, and minority language studies. The volume advances our understanding of linguistic change in a mediatized world in three ways. First, it introduces the notions of sociolinguistic change and mediatization to create a broader theoretical framing than the one offered by ‘the media’ and ‘language change’. Second, it takes the discussion beyond the notions of ‘influence’ and ‘effect’ and the binary distinction of ‘media’ vs. ‘community language’. Third, it examines the relation of sociolinguistic change and mediatization and from five complementary viewpoints: media influence on linguistic structure; media engagement in interaction; change in mass and new media language; language-ideological change; and the role of media for minority languages. Bringing these strands of sociolinguistic scholarship together, this volume examines their shared references and common lines of thinking.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 17. Dez 2021) 0aLinguistic changexSocial aspects. 0aMass media and language. 0aMass mediaxInfluence. 0aSociolinguistics. 4aMassenmedien/Sprache. 4aMediatisierung/kommunikatives Handeln. 4aSprachwandel. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aLanguage Change.  aMedia Influence on Language.  aMediatization.  aSociolinguistic Change.1 aAndroutsopoulos, Jannis, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAndroutsopoulos, Jannis, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aBuchstaller, Isabelle, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCotter, Colleen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoupland, Nikolas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeumert, Ana, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGeorgakopoulou, Alexandra, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHepp, Andreas, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIorio, Josh, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aJohnstone, Barbara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly-Holmes, Helen, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKerswill, Paul, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKristiansen, Tore, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLuginbühl, Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLytra, Vally, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMoriarty, Mairéad, econtributor.4ct